{
  "doc_id": "4381",
  "text": "Adoptive cell therapy is a new therapeutic strategy based on the modulation, manipulation, and selection of autologous T cells in vitro to overcome the tolerance of the immune system to tumour cells. The T cells can be harvested from tils and reinfused into the donor patient after population expansion is ensured. Lymphocyte T cells can also be harvested from peripheral blood, with those that recognize tumour antigens being selectively expanded. Alternatively, lymphocyte T cells can be genetically engineered either by modifying a T cell receptor for a cancer antigen (\"transgenic T cell receptor\") or by adding a chimeric antigen receptor that recognizes a specific cancer antigen [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . To our knowledge, the use of tils has never been investigated in sarcoma-specific cohorts, and the use of activated natural killer cells has been limited to case reports [CITATION_5] .",
